iants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pilkington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northwestern): habitational name from a place in Lancashire. The placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Pīleca</i> or <i>Pīloc</i> + patronymic <i>-ing</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The surname is established in Ireland, where its presence was first recorded in the early 15th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Pilkerton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkinton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkenton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":64,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Pilkington I was born in 1160, in Pilkington, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Alexander de Pilkington, was 51 and his mother, Ursula de Rivington, was 48. He had at least 2 sons with Ursula de Workedleigh. He lived in Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom in 1202. He died in 1232, in Pilkington, Lancashire, England, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1160–1232":"1160–1232","1155–1202":"1155–1202","1162–1213":"1162–1213","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1225–1291":"1225–1291","–Male":"Surnud","1110–1180":"1110–1180","1112–1178":"1112–1178","about 1180":"umbes 1180","20 April 1933":"20 aprill 1933","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","1250":"1250","1162":"1162","1160":"1160","1291":"1291","1180":"1180","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1178":"1178","1112":"1112","1232":"1232","1155":"1155","Rivington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Rivington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hyde Park, Cache, Utah, United States":"Hyde Park, Cache, Utah, Ameerika Ühendriigid","England":"England","Pilkington Manor, Lancashire, England":"Pilkington, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1160–1232":"1160–1232","1155–1202":"1155–1202","1162–1213":"1162–1213","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1225–1291":"1225–1291","–Male":"Kuollut","1110–1180":"1110–1180","1112–1178":"1112–117